=███████████████████: `We Welcome Probe Into Power ████et'  (This article
was originally published ███████)       By █████████████     OF █████████
NEWSWIRES    ███████████ (Dow Jones)--When ██████████ Attorney General ████
███████ completes ███ investigation into possible "collusion" in the
wholesale electricity market by generators, energy companies say ██ will
probably find the same thing ██████████████ found in ███████████ safe:
nothing.  Still, those companies that own generation in the state say they
welcome the probe into the power market by Attorney General ████ ███████.
"We have done nothing wrong at all," said ████████████, spokesman for █████████████████████████ (███). "Our plants have been running ██████████ long.
Prices are high throughout the west. We wouldn't invest $1.7 billion in new
generation and then try and rig the market."  For ███████████████████,
utilities, lawmakers and other market participants have made allegations
that generators are manipulating the market and are largely responsible for
the price spikes.  ██████'s office said an investigation is still pending.
State regulators are also conducting their own investigation, the findings
of which will be submitted to the governor and ████████████████████████████████████████ by ███████████████████.  Allegations Said Unsubstantiated  There
isn't a shred of evidence to support allegations, said ███████████████████,
director of the University of ██████████, Berkley's, ████████████████.
"There are no antitrust laws that state you can't charge a premium price for
power," ██████████ said. "Manipulation is a bad word. That's used in the
commodities market to find a loophole and take advantage of the rules.  "I
would say this is exercising market power. ... If you want to charge high
prices you can. These are guys who play against each other every day. There
is no sort of collusion that would interest the justice department ... ."
The reason for the inquiry ordered By Gov. ██████████, ██ said, is as a
consequence of █████████ consumers being the first in the nation to pay
market-based rates for electricity.  The high wholesale costs paid by
utility █████████ Gas & Electric, a unit of █████████████ (███), were passed
on to ratepayers and resulted in utility bills more than doubling.  Gov.
█████ ordered the inquiry and asked federal regulators to conduct their own
investigation as well.  ██████ (DYN) President ███████████████ also says
that an investigation "will turn up nothing."  So why conduct one?  "This is
a very politically charged issue," █████████ said. "When something goes
wrong you have to find someone to point the finger at."  A source in the
governor's office said █████ is aware that Attorney General ███████'s
investigation may turn up nothing, but Gov. █████ "has a responsibility to
███ constituents."  Supply vs. Demand  What the investigation will turn up
is evidence that there is a shortage of power in the state and not enough
power plants being built to meet increasing demand, said ████████████,
chairman and chief executive officer of the ██████████ Independent System
Operator.  ██████ said ██ doesn't believe that there is anything wrong with
the way generators sell their power and 98% of the time the market works
well.  "Is it market abuse to bid at the price cap ($250 per megawatt-hour)
knowing that you're 1,000 ██ short? I have trouble identifying that as
market power abuse," ██████ said.  Despite some proposed regulatory changes,
such as bid caps on wholesale energy prices and a rate freeze for SDG&E
customers, ███████████, ██████, ████████████ (SO) and ███████ (RLI) all
still plan to invest in generation in the state.  That's a different stance
than the companies took ███████████ when the ███ reduced the wholesale price
cap in the real-time market to $250/██h.  "At ██████████████████ the market
is short power and you got to get people to build new generation," said
██████'s █████████. "We got a big investment in ██████████. We're not
walking away from that."  -By █████████████, ███████████████████;
