Complaint
(This article was originally published ███████)
██████████ (Dow Jones)--██████████'s power grid administrator ██████ urged
federal regulators to reject a complaint from power producers seeking
compensation in the event out-of-state power transactions are curtailed
during an extreme power grid emergency.
The independent system operator told ████████████████████████████████████████ that the power producers seek compensation in the event of a
"situation that never has occurred any time since the ███ began operations,
and if it were to occur in the future, would do so rarely."
The ███ noted that its tariff governing access to the state's grid already
allows for compensation in the event of curtailed exports, and decried the
power producers' complaint as "a collateral attack" on a previous ████ order
rejecting claims that the tariff failed to provide adequate compensation.
Curtailing scheduled power transactions and exports would be a last resort
measure taken only after other options have been exhausted, the ███ said.
The power producers should adjust their contracts to factor in the risk of
interruption in the event of a state-wide grid emergency, the ███ said.
The ███'s objections were echoed by the state's electricity distribution
utilities and ██████████ regulators.
They complained that the power producers are merely trying to get out from
under the price controls the ███ has imposed in an effort to rein in
skyrocketing power prices ███████████.
The generators "knew when they purchased ██████████ power plants and when
they entered into their export contracts that the ███ could alter their
schedules in an emergency. For them to ask the commission to make it even
more expensive, and hence, more difficult, for the ███ to maintain grid
reliability in ██████████ is irresponsible," said Southern ██████████
██████, a unit of ██████ International (EIX).
"The complaint is a sham," declared the ██████████ Public Utilities
Commission.
"The true intent of the complaint ... is to avoid the ███ price caps by
making sales to affiliates or cooperating entities located out of state, and
sell the power back to the ███ at uncapped prices reflecting the generators'
market power," the ███ said, calling for ████ to summarily reject the
complaint.
"The complaint is factually unsupported, legally unfounded, complains of
conduct consistent with the ███'s authority under pertinent ████ decisions,
and seeks to avoid the price cap," the ███ said.
But power marketers and other power producers voiced support for the
complaint, filed ██████ by ███████ Power Generation Inc. (███), ██████ Power
████eting Inc. (DYN) and ███████████████ ██████████ (SO).
"By subjecting curtailed energy transactions to its maximum purchase price
of $250, and simply ignoring the financial impact on sellers, the Cal ███
would be overtly discriminating against export transactions and market
participants who schedule energy for export," said █████████████████████████████████████, ████████████████████████ representing competitive power
producers.
"It is critical that power producers ... know with certainty that the
curtailment of scheduled energy exports by Cal ███ will be compensated,"
said █████████████████████████████████
"Now that the ███ Governing Board has lowered purchase price caps to $250,
it is significantly more likely that the curtailment of exports will occur
more frequently. Less energy will be imported into ██████████ and more
energy will leave ██████████ in search of higher prices," said Williams
Energy ████eting & Trading Co. in support of the complaint's call for actual
damages and lost opportunity costs.
At least one power purchaser voiced support for the producers' position as
well.
"It seems a very basic point that if the Cal ███ must divert the
transactions of others to meet its own loads, that is should pay the full
costs of doing so," said the Northern ██████████ Power Agency.
